go-Kinshasa: Le 8 ao\u00fbt 1960, Albert Kalonji proclame l'autonomie du Sud-Kasa\u00ef|date=15 August 2008|newspaper=[[Le Potentiel]]|url=http://fr.allafrica.com/stories/200808150585.html|accessdate=25 November 2014}}\n* {{cite book|ref={{harvid|Nugent|2004}}|last=Nugent|first=Paul|title=Africa since Independence: A Comparative History|publisher=Palgrave-MacMillan|year=2004|location=New York|isbn=978-0-333-68273-9}}\n* {{cite book|ref={{harvid|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007}}|last=Nzongola-Ntalaja|first=Georges|authorlink=Georges Nzongola-Ntalaja|title=The Congo, From Leopold to Kabila: A People's History|url=https://archive.org/details/congofromleopold00geor|url-access=registration|date=2007|publisher=Palgrave|location=New York|isbn=978-1-84277-053-5|edition=3rd}}\n* {{cite book| last = O'Ballance| first = Edgar| title = The Congo-Zaire Experience, 1960\u201398| publisher = Springer| location = London| edition = illustrated| date = 1999| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=vfCADAAAQBAJ&dq=| isbn = 9780230286481| ref= harv}}\n* {{cite web| url = http://www.sciencespo.fr/mass-violence-war-massacre-resistance/en/document/chronology-democratic-republic-congozaire-1960-1997| title = Chronology of the Democratic Republic of Congo/Zaire (1960-1997)| last = Olivier| first = Lanotte| date = 6 April 2010| website = [[Online Encyclopedia of Mass Violence]]| ref = harv| access-date = 29 April 2017}}\n* {{cite book| editor-last = Omasombo Tshonda| editor-first = Jean| title = Kasa\u00ef-Oriental : Un n\u0153ud gordien dans l'espace congolais| publisher =  Mus\u00e9e royal de l\u2019Afrique centrale| series = Provinces| date = 2014| location = Tervuren| language = French| url = http://www.africamuseum.be/sites/default/files/media/docs/research/publications/rmca/online/monographies-provinces/kasai-oriental.pdf| isbn = 978-9-4916-1524-5 | ref = harv}}\n* {{cite journal| title = Onze mois de crise politique au Congo| journal = Courrier hebdomadaire du CRISP| issue = 120| pages = 1\u201324| publisher = Centre de recherche et d'information socio-politiques| date = 1961| language = French| url = http://www.cairn.info/revue-courrier-hebdomadaire-du-crisp-1961-30-page-1.htm| doi = 10.3917/cris.120.0001| ref = {{harvid|CRISP|1961}}}}\n* {{cite book| last = Othen| first = Christopher| title = Katanga 1960\u201363: Mercenaries, Spies and the African Nation that Waged War on the World| publisher = The History Press| edition = illustrated| date = 2015| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=d3MTDQAAQBAJ&dq=| isbn = 9780750965804| ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref={{harvid|Packham|1996}}|last=Packham|first=Eric S.|title=Freedom and Anarchy|publisher=Nova Science|location=New York|isbn=1-56072-232-0|year=1996}}\n* {{cite book|ref={{harvid|Pakenham|1992}}|last=Pakenham|first=Thomas|authorlink=Thomas Pakenham (historian)|title=The Scramble for Africa: the White Man's Conquest of the Dark Continent from 1876 to 1912|year=1992|publisher=Abacus|location=London|isbn=978-0-349-10449-2|edition=13th}}\n* {{cite book|ref ={{harvid|Pandey|Geschiere|2003}}|last = Pandey|first = Gyanendra|last2 = Geschiere|first2 = Peter| title = The Forging of Nationhood| publisher = Manohar| date = 2003| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=CT6FAAAAMAAJ&q=| isbn = 9788173044250}}\n* {{cite book|ref={{harvid|UNCHS|1991}}|title=The Management of Secondary Cities in Sub-Saharan Africa: Traditional and Modern Institutional Arrangements|publisher=UNCHS (Habitat)|location=Nairobi|year=1991}}\n* {{cite book| last = Simmonds| first = R.| title = Legal problems arising from the United Nations military operations in the Congo| publisher = Springer| edition = illustrated| date = 2012| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=u4X1CAAAQBAJ&dq=| isbn = 9789401192675| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Stapleton| first = Timothy J.| title = A History of Genocide in Africa| publisher = ABC-CLIO| date = 2017| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=wYuNDgAAQBAJ&dq=| isbn = 9781440830525 | ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref={{harvid|Turner|2007}}|last1=Turner|first1=Thomas|title=The Congo Wars: Conflict, Myth, and Reality|date=2007|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-84277-688-9|edition=2nd}}\n* {{cite book|ref={{harvid|Willame|1972}}|last=Willame|first=Jean-Claude|title=Patrimonialism and Political Change in the Congo|year=1972|publisher=Stanford University Press|location=Stanford|isbn=0-8047-0793-6|url=https://archive.org/details/patrimonialismpo0000will}}\n* {{cite book| last = Young| first = M. Crawford| title = Politics in the Congo: Decolonization and Independence|location= Princeton| publisher = Princeton University Press| date = 1965| ref = harv| oclc= 307971}}\n* {{cite book|ref={{harvid|Zeilig|2008}}|last1=Zeilig|first1=Leo|title=Lumumba: Africa's Lost Leader|date=2008|publisher=Haus|location=London|isbn=978-1-905791-02-6}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Dedeken|first=No\u00ebl C.|title=Chim\u00e8res Baluba: Le Sud-Kasa\u00ef, 1960\u20131962 \u00e0 feu et \u00e0 sang|date=1978|publisher=Dedeken Editeur|location=Brussels|oclc=70737994}}\n*{{cite book|last=De Witte|first=Ludo|authorlink=Ludo De Witte|title=The Assassination of Lumumba|date=2002|publisher=Verso|location=London|isbn=1-85984-410-3|edition=Trans.}}\n*{{cite book|last=Kalonji Ditunga Mulopwe|first=Albert|authorlink=Albert Kalonji|title=Congo 1960, la s\u00e9cession du Sud-Kasa\u00ef: La v\u00e9rit\u00e9 du Mulopwe|publisher=L'Harmattan|location=Paris|year=2005|isbn=2-7475-8132-2}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Keller|first=Edmond J.|title=Secessionism in Africa|journal=Journal of African Policy Studies|volume=13|number=1|year=2007|pages=1\u201326}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Muyumba|first=Valentine Kanyinda|year=2004|title=Luba-Kasai: A Working Bibliography|journal=Electronic Journal of Africana Bibliography|volume=9|doi=10.17077/1092-9576.1001|doi-access=free}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|South Kasai}}\n*[http://www.lephareonline.net/congo-zaire-lempire-du-crime-permanent-le-massacre-de-bakwanga/ Congo-Za\u00efre : l'empire du crime permanent : le massacre de Bakwanga] at ''[[Le Phare (newspaper)|Le Phare]]''\n*[http://akemasbl.canalblog.com/archives/2010/03/09/17178945.html La V\u00e9rit\u00e9 sur le Sud-Kasa\u00ef] at the ''Association Kasayienne d'Entre-aide Mutuelle''\n\n{{coord|06|09|S|23|36|E|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:History of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Separatism in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Former unrecognized countries]]\n[[Category:Congo Crisis]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1960]]\n[[Category:1960 establishments in Africa]]\n[[Category:1962 disestablishments in Africa]]\n[[Category:Former polities of the Cold War]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox Former Country\n|native_name = ''Sud-Kasa\u00ef''\n|conventional_long_name = South Kasai\n|common_name = South Kasai\n|status = [[List of historical unrecognized states|Unrecognised state]]\n|p1 = Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)\n|flag_p1 = Flag of Congo-L\u00e9opoldville (1960-1963).svg\n|s1 = Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)\n|flag_s1 = Flag of Congo-L\u00e9opoldville (1960-1963).svg\n|image_flag = Flag of South Kasai.svg\n|image_coat = Emblem of South Kasai.svg\n|image_map = South Kasai in Congo 1961.svg\n|image_map_caption = Map of the Congo in 1961 with South Kasai highlighted in red, bordered by [[State of Katanga|secessionist Katanga]] to the south.\n|national_anthem = \n|capital = [[Mbuji-Mayi|Bakwanga]]\n|government_type = ''[[De Jure]]'':<br>Autonomous [[federated state]] of the [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Republic of the Congo]]<br>\n''[[De Facto]]'':<br>Independent [[Semi-presidential system|semi-presidential]], later [[Monarchy|monarchic]], [[ethnocracy]]\n|leader1 =\n|era = Congo Crisis\n|event_pre = [[Congo Crisis#Independence|Congolese independence]]\n|date_pre = 30 June 1960\n|event_start = Unilateral secession\n|date_start = 9 August\n|year_start = 1960\n|event1 = Monarchy proclaimed\n|date_event1 = 12 April 1961\n|event2 = Arrest of Kalonji\n|date_event2 = 30 December 1961\n|event3 = Coup d'\u00e9tat\n|date_event3 = 29 September 1962\n|event_end = [[Congo Crisis#United Nations escalation and the end of the Katangese secession|Dissolution]]\n|date_end = 5 October\n|year_end = 1962\n|religion=\n|currency = [[Congolese franc]]\n|stat_pop1 = 1,000,000\n|stat_year2 = 1961 est.\n|stat_year1 = 1961 est.;\n|stat_area1 = 30,000\n|footnote_a =\n|today = {{flag|Democratic Republic of the Congo}}\n}}\n'''South Kasai''' ({{lang-fr|Sud-Kasa\u00ef}}) was an [[List of historical unrecognized states and dependencies|unrecognised]] [[Secession|secessionist state]] within the [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Republic of the Congo]] (the modern-day [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]){{efn|Not to be confused with the neighbouring state currently known as the [[Republic of the Congo]], formerly the [[French Congo]], with its capital at [[Brazzaville]]. The state's name changed to the Democratic Republic of the Congo in August 1964.{{sfn|EISA|2002}} }} which was semi-independent between 1960 and 1962. Initially proposed as only a province, South Kasai sought full [[Autonomous administrative division|autonomy]] in similar circumstances to the much larger neighbouring state of [[State of Katanga|Katanga]], to its south, during the political turmoil arising from the independence of the [[Belgian Congo]] known as the [[Congo Crisis]]. Unlike Katanga, however, South Kasai did not explicitly declare full independence from the Republic of the Congo or reject Congolese sovereignty.\n\nThe South Kasaian leader and main advocate, [[Albert Kalonji]], who had represented a faction of the [[African Nationalism|nationalist movement]] (the ''[[Mouvement National Congolais|Mouvement National Congolais-Kalonji]]'' or MNC-K) before decolonisation, exploited ethnic tensions between his own ethnic group, the [[Luba people|Baluba]],{{efn|In most [[Bantu languages]], the [[prefix#Bantu languages|prefix]] ''ba-'' is added to a human noun to form a plural. As such, ''Baluba'' refers collectively to members of the [[Luba people|Luba ethnic group]]. Its adjectival form is ''Muluba''.}} and the [[Lulua people|Bena Lulua]] to create a Luba-focused state in the group's traditional heartland in the south-eastern parts of the [[Kasai region]]. As sectarian violence broke out across the country, the state declared its secession from the Congo on 9 August 1960{{efn|Some sources instead date the state's proclamation to 8 August.{{sfn|Le Potentiel|2008}}}} and its government and called for the Baluba living in the rest of the Congo to return to their \"homeland\". Kalonji was appointed President. Although the South Kasaian government claimed to form an autonomous part of a [[federalism|federal]] Congo-wide state, it exercised a degree of regional autonomy and even produced its own constitution and postage stamps. The state, supported by foreign powers, particularly [[Belgium]], and funded by [[diamond]] exports, managed numerous crises, including those caused by the large emigration of Luba refugees, but became increasingly militarist and repressive.\n\nSoon after its secession, South Kasaian and Congolese troops clashed after the Congolese central government ordered an offensive against it. The resulting campaign, planned to be the first act of a larger action against Katanga, was accompanied by widespread massacres of Baluba and a refugee crisis termed a [[genocide]] by some contemporaries. The state was rapidly overrun by Congolese troops. The violence in the suppression of Kasai provided much legitimacy to [[Joseph Kasa-Vubu]]'s deposition of [[Patrice Lumumba]] from the office of Prime Minister in late 1960 and Lumumba's later arrest and assassination. As a result, South Kasai remained on relatively good terms with the new Congolese government from 1961. Its leaders, including Kalonji himself, served in both the South Kasaian government and the Congolese parliament. South Kasai continued to exercise quasi-independence while Congolese and [[United Nations]] troops were able to move through the territory without conflict with the South Kasaian [[gendarmerie]]. In April 1961, Kalonji took the royal title ''Mulopwe'' (\"King of the Baluba\") to tie the state more closely to the pre-colonial [[Kingdom of Luba|Luba Empire]]. The act divided the South Kasaian authorities and Kalonji was disavowed by the majority of South Kasai's parliamentary representatives in [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]].{{efn|During the period of [[Mobutu Sese Seko]]'s rule in the Congo (1965\u201397), large numbers of place names created during the colonial period were changed as part of his ''[[Authenticit\u00e9 (Zaire)|authenticit\u00e9]]'' campaign. For the modern equivalents, see [[former place names in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]].}} In December 1961, Kalonji was arrested on a legal pretext in L\u00e9opoldville and imprisoned, and [[Ferdinand Kazadi]] assumed power as acting head of state. UN and Congolese troops occupied South Kasai. In September 1962, shortly after his escape from prison and return to South Kasai, Kalonji was ousted by a military [[coup d'\u00e9tat]] which forced him into exile and brought the secession to an end.\n\nThe end of South Kasai's secession is usually held to be either December 1961, the date of Kalonji's arrest, or October 1962 with the anti-Kalonji coup d'\u00e9tat and final arrival of government troops.\n\n==Background==\n\n===Colonial rule===\n[[File:StoryoftheCongoFreeState 144b.jpg|thumb|[[Luba people|Luba]] chiefs of the [[Congo Free State]], {{circa}} 1900]]\n[[Colonization of the Congo|European colonial rule in the Congo]] began in the late 19th century. [[Leopold II of Belgium|King Leopold II]] of [[Belgium]], frustrated by his country's lack of international power and prestige, attempted to persuade the Belgian government to support colonial expansion around the then-largely unexplored [[Congo Basin]]. The Belgian government's ambivalence about the idea led Leopold to eventually create the colony on his own account. With support from a number of Western countries, who viewed Leopold as a useful [[Buffer state|buffer]] between rival colonial powers, Leopold achieved international recognition for a personal colony, the [[Congo Free State]], in 1885.{{sfn|Pakenham|1992|pp=253\u20135}} The [[Luba Empire]], the largest regional power in the [[Kasai region]], was annexed into the new state in 1889. By the turn of the century, the violence of Free State officials against indigenous Congolese and the ruthless system of economic extraction had led to intense diplomatic pressure on Belgium to take official control of the country, which it did in 1908, creating the [[Belgian Congo]].{{sfn|Pakenham|1992|pp=588\u20139}}\n\nBelgian rule in the Congo was based around the \"colonial trinity\" (''trinit\u00e9 coloniale'') of [[Government|state]], [[Christianity|missionary]] and [[Privately held company|private company]] interests. The privileging of Belgian commercial interests meant that large amounts of capital flowed into the Congo and that individual regions became [[economic specialization|specialised]]. On many occasions, the interests of the government and private enterprise became closely tied and the state helped companies break strikes and remove other barriers imposed by the indigenous population.{{sfn|Turner|2007|p=28}} The country was split into hierarchically-organised administrative subdivisions, and run uniformly according to a set \"native policy\" (''politique indig\u00e8ne'') \u2013 in contrast to the British and the French, who generally favoured the system of [[indirect rule]] whereby traditional leaders were retained in positions of authority under colonial oversight.{{sfn|Turner|2007|p=29}}\n\n===Ethnicity===\nBefore the start of the colonial period, the region of South Kasai formed part of the Luba Empire, a federation of local kingdoms with a degree of cultural uniformity. During the 17th and 18th centuries, the Baluba spread across large parts of the Kasai-Katanga savannah along the [[Kasai River|Kasai river basin]] and eventually developed into a number of ethnic subgroups, notably the Luba-Kasai and the Luba-Katanga. Although never united into a single centralised state, the groups retained a degree of emotional attachment based around shared origin myths and cultural practices.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=102}} Other groups, like the [[Songye people|Songye]] and the [[Kanyok people|Kanyok]], also had long histories in the Kasai region.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|pp=102\u20133}}\n\nOne of the major legacies of colonial rule in Kasai was the arbitrary redivision of the population into new ethnic groups. Despite the shared language ([[Luba-Kasai language|Tshiluba]]) and culture of the two groups, colonial administrators believed the inhabitants of the [[Lulua River|Lulua river]] area to be ethnically different from the Baluba and dubbed them the Bena Lulua. The colonists believed the Baluba to be more intelligent, hardworking and open to new ideas than the Bena Lulua who were believed to be more reactionary and stupid. As a result, from the 1930s, the state began to treat the two groups differently and applied different policies to each and promoted the Baluba to positions above other ethnicities.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=103}}\n\nDuring the 1950s when the Belgians began to fear that the rise of a powerful Luba elite would become a threat to colonial rule, the administration began to support Lulua organisations. This further contributed to the growing ethnic polarisation between the two groups. In 1952, an organisation called the ''Lulua Fr\u00e8res'' (Lulua Brothers) was established to campaign for socio-economic advancement of the Lulua group and became an unofficial representative of the Bena Lulua. In 1959, Luba-Lulua animosity was brought to a head by the discovery of a colonial proposal to move Luba farmers out of Lulua land to the less fertile land on Luba territory. As a result, hostility increased and violent clashes broke out. In August 1959, Luba demonstrations against the plan which were violently repressed by the colonial military and police.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=104}}\n\n===Nationalist movement and Congolese politics===\n[[File:Anefo 910-9740 De Congolese2.jpg|thumb|upright|150px|[[Patrice Lumumba]] split with Kalonji in 1959 and denied his supporters roles in central government.]]\n\n====Congolese nationalism====\nAn anti-colonial [[Pan-Africanism|Pan-African]] and [[African nationalism|nationalist movement]] developed in the Belgian Congo during the 1950s, primarily among the ''[[\u00e9volu\u00e9]]'' class (the urbanised black [[bourgeoisie]]). The movement was divided into a number of parties and groups which were broadly divided on ethnic and geographical lines and opposed to one another.{{sfn|Freund|1998|p=199}} The largest, the ''[[Mouvement National Congolais]]'' (MNC), was a [[united front]] organisation dedicated to achieving independence \"within a reasonable\" time.{{sfn|Zeilig|2008|p=64}} It was created around a charter which was signed by, among others, [[Patrice Lumumba]], [[Cyrille Adoula]] and [[Joseph Ileo]].{{sfn|Zeilig|2008|pp=64\u20135}} Lumumba became a leading figure and by the end of 1959, the party claimed to have 58,000 members.{{sfn|Zeilig|2008|p=76}} However, many found the MNC was too moderate. A number of other parties emerged, distinguished by their radicalism, support for [[federalism]] or [[Centralized government|centralism]] and affiliation to certain [[ethnic nationalism|ethnic groupings]]. The MNC's main rival was the ''[[ABAKO|Alliance des Bakongo]]'' (ABAKO) led by [[Joseph Kasa-Vubu]], a more radical party supported among the [[Kongo people]] in the north, and [[Moise Tshombe]]'s ''[[CONAKAT|Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration des Associations Tribales du Katanga]]'' (CONAKAT), a strongly federalist party in the southern [[Katanga Province]].{{sfn|Zeilig|2008|p=74}}\n\n====Kalonji-Lumumba split and polarisation====\n[[File:Albert Kalonji.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Albert Kalonji]] broke with Lumumba and later led the secession of South Kasai.]]\nAlthough it was the largest of the African nationalist parties, the MNC had many different factions within it that took differing stances on a number of issues. It was increasingly polarised between moderate ''\u00e9volu\u00e9s'' and the more radical mass membership.{{sfn|Zeilig|2008|pp=82\u20133}} A radical and federalist faction headed by Ileo and [[Albert Kalonji]] split away in July 1959, but failed to induce mass defections by other MNC members. The dissident faction became known as the MNC-Kalonji (MNC-K), while the majority group became the MNC-Lumumba (MNC-L). The split divided the party's support base into those who endured with Lumumba, chiefly in the [[Kisangani|Stanleyville]] region in the north-east, and those who backed the MNC-K, popular in the south and among Kalonji's own ethnic group, the Baluba.{{sfn|Zeilig|2008|pp=83\u20135}} The MNC-K later formed a [[cartel]] with ABAKO and the ''[[Parti Solidaire Africain]]'' (PSA) to call for a united, but federalised, Congo.{{sfn|Haskin|2005|p=16}}\n\nThe 1960 elections degenerated into an \"anti-Baluba plebiscite\" in Kasai as the Luba MNC-K succeeded in obtaining a [[Plurality (voting)|plurality]] but failed to take control of the provincial government. Instead, Lumumba promoted a Lulua candidate, [[Barth\u00e9lemy Mukenge]], as provincial president while Kalonji was denied an important ministerial portfolio in [[Lumumba Government|Lumumba's government]]. Kalonji refused Lumumba's offer of the Agriculture portfolio.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=104}} Mukenge attempted to form a government of unity, even offering MNC-K member [[Joseph Ngalula]] a place in his cabinet. Ngalula rejected the offer and on 14 June the MNC-K resolved to establish an alternative government under his leadership.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2014|pp=181\u2013182}}<ref name= mukenge>{{cite news| title = Mukenge Announces Kasai Government| author = Belgian Congo Home Service|newspaper= Daily Report: Foreign Radio Broadcasts| location = L\u00e9opoldville|page= I1| date = 17 June 1960| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=EC8jAQAAMAAJ&q=}}</ref>\n\nThe Kalonjists, who felt rejected and marginalised by the central government, began supporting alternative parties. Among them, the Kalonjists supported Tshombe's CONAKAT party in nearby Katanga which, because of its strongly federalist stance, opposed to Lumumba's conception of a strong central government based in the capital [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]]. As part of this, the Kalonjists supported CONAKAT against their main local rivals, the ''[[BALUBAKAT|Association G\u00e9n\u00e9rale des Baluba du Katanga]]'' (BALUBAKAT) party led by [[Jason Sendwe]], which, although it represented the Baluba of Katanga Province, was in favour of centralism.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=105}} The Kalonjists, who believed themselves to be acting on behalf of all the Luba-Kasai, created an animosity between the Luba-Kasai and the Luba-Katanga but also failed to gain the full support of CONAKAT, much of which had racial prejudice against the Baluba and supported only the \"authentic Katangese\".{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=105}}\n\n==Secession==\n{{Congolese independence}}\n===Persecution of the Baluba===\nThe Republic of the Congo received independence on 30 June 1960 under a joint government of Kasa-Vubu and Lumumba. The Chamber of the L\u00e9opoldville Parliament had convened one week prior to review Lumumba's cabinet and give it a vote of confidence. During the session, Kalonji, in his capacity as an elected deputy, criticised the proposed cabinet, expressing dissatisfaction that his party had not been consulted in its formation and declaring that he was proud not to be included in an \"anti-Baluba\" and \"anti-Batshoke\"{{efn|The Batshoke were an ethnic group that was allied with the Baluba.{{sfn|Olivier|2010|loc= 1 THE CONGOLESE CRISIS (1960-1963)}}}} government which had shown contempt for the wishes of Kasai's people. He also stated his intentions to encourage the Baluba and Batshoke to refrain from participating in the government and to take his own steps to form a sovereign state centered in [[Mbuji-Mayi|Bakwanga]].{{sfn|Kanza|1994|p=101}} \n\nOn 26 June, MNC-K officials petitioned the L\u00e9opoldville Parliament to peacefully divide the Province of Kasai along the lines suggested by Kalonji. The motion, which would have required the modification of the Congo's new constitution (''Loi fondamentale''), was received by a legislature divided between Lumumba and Kasa-Vubu factions and no agreement could be reached.{{sfn|Le Potentiel|2008}}\n\nIn the aftermath of independence, ethnic tensions flared up across the country, much of it directed against the Baluba, and a number of violent clashes occurred.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=105}} On 3 July the central government ordered the arrest of the rival Kalonjist Kasai government, precipitating unrest in Luluabourg.{{sfn|O'Ballance|1999|p=15}} Despite rejecting earlier proposals for Luba repatriations to the province in January 1960, the Kalonjists made an official call to the Baluba across the Congo to return to their Kasaian \"homeland\" on 16 July. Initially, the Kalonjists envisaged the division of [[Kasai Province]] in two in order to allow for the creation of a quasi-autonomous MNC-K and Luba-dominated provincial government.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=105}} The proposed province was termed the Federated State of South Kasai (''\u00c9tat f\u00e9d\u00e9ratif du Sud-Kasa\u00ef'').{{sfn|Dufresne|2011|p=26}} Rapidly, however, Kalonji realised that the chaos in the rest of the Congo could be used to secede unilaterally and declare full local independence.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=105}} This decision was further re-enforced by the full secession of the [[State of Katanga]] (''\u00c9tat du Katanga''), led by Tshombe, on 11 July 1960.{{sfn|Nugent|2004|p=85}} Kalonji visited Katanga at the start of August 1960, shortly after its secession, where, on the 8 August, he declared that Kasai \"must be divided at all costs.\"{{sfn|Le Potentiel|2008}}\n\n===Secession===\n[[File:Joseph Ngalula.jpg|thumb|[[Joseph Ngalula]] was appointed Prime Minister of South Kasai.|100px]]\nOn 9 August 1960, Kalonji, still in Katanga, declared the region of south-eastern Kasai to be the new Mining State of South Kasai (''\u00c9tat minier du Sud-Kasa\u00ef'') or Autonomous State of South Kasai (''\u00c9tat autonome du Sud-Kasa\u00ef'').{{efn|In the period shortly after its formation, South Kasai's official title remained unclear. Beside ''\u00c9tat autonome'' or ''\u00c9tat minier'', it is sometimes termed Province of the Luba (''Province muluba'') or Mining Province (''Province minier''). The use of the word \"state\" (''\u00e9tat'') was deliberately ambiguous, allowing Kalonji to avoid specifying whether the South Kasai claimed to independence as a nation-state in imitation of Katanga, or as a province within the Congo.{{sfn|Le Potentiel|2008}} }}{{sfn|Packham|1996|p=37}}{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=105}}\n\nUnlike Katanga, however, South Kasai's secession did not explicitly mean the rejection of its position within the Republic of the Congo. Rather, it resembled the self-declared local governments in [[\u00c9quateur (former province)|\u00c9quateur Province]].{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=35}} The \"[[Autonomous administrative division|Autonomous State]]\" title was chosen in order to re-enforce the impression that the secession was not a rejection of Congolese sovereignty, but the creation of a federally-governed region of the Congo.{{sfn|Dufresne|2011|p=26}} The secession had some support among journalists, intellectuals and politicians in L\u00e9opoldville, with one newspaper calling it \"a model by which the many new states now mushrooming in the Congo might form a new federation\".{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=35}} In practice South Kasai had considerably more independence than a regular province and, by mandating its own federated powers unilaterally, was effectively seceding from the Congo.{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=66}} It also did not forward any taxes to the central government and locals\u2014drawing a comparison to the secessionist state to the south\u2014sometimes referred to it as \"Little Katanga\".<ref name= halberstam>{{cite news| last = Halberstam| first = David| title = Rich Diamond Mines at Stake In Congo-South Kasai Struggle : Secession Continues Despite Arrest of State's Leader by Central Regime\u2013 Negotiations on Status in Progress| newspaper = The New York Times| page = 2| date = 19 February 1962| id = {{ProQuest|115673183}}}}</ref> Despite this, Kalonji and members of his party continued to sit as deputies in the Congolese Parliament in L\u00e9opoldville.{{sfn|Dufresne|2011|p=26}}\n\nKalonji was declared President and Joseph Ngalula Prime Minister. Although the Luba-Kasai had never lived in a single state before, Kalonji was able to gain the broad support of the Luba chiefs for the secession.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=105}} He was able to portray the secession internationally as the result of the persecution and the failure of the Congolese government to sufficiently protect the Baluba in the rest of the Congo.{{sfn|Nugent|2004|p=86}} At its height, South Kasai numbered around a million inhabitants and {{convert|30,000|km2}} of territory,{{sfn|Dufresne|2011|p=26}} though its borders frequently changed.{{sfn|CRISP|1961|loc=paragraph 5}} The state's capital was Bakwanga.{{sfn|Dufresne|2011|p=26}}\n\n===Governance===\nOnce established in power, Kalonji positioned himself personally as \"[[Big man (anthropology)|big man]]\" and [[patronage|patron]] from whom state power originated.{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=66}} Tribal leaders from Luba and other ethnic groups enjoyed a close, client-like relationship with Kalonji himself and received preferential treatment in exchange for services rendered.{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=66}} In particular, Kalonji was reliant on tribal leaders to mobilise paramilitaries to support the South Kasaian army.{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=66}}\n\n[[File:South Kasai overprint stamps.jpg|thumb|170px|upright|[[Postage stamps and postal history of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|Postage stamps of South Kasai]], overprinted onto earlier issues of the Belgian Congo{{sfn|Dufresne|2011|p=26}}|left]]\nThe immediate internal problems faced by South Kasai were large number of unsettled Luba refugees and internal dissent from non-Luba minorities. The state was able to direct money from diamond exporting and foreign support to fund public services which allowed Luba refugees to be settled in employment. Social services were \"relatively well-run\".{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=106}} State revenue was estimated to total $30,000,000 annually.<ref name= garrison>{{cite news| last = Garrison| first = Lloyd| title = Kalonji, 'King' of South Kasai, Out of Congo Jail| newspaper = The New York Times| page = 22| date = 9 September 1962| id = {{ProQuest|115736669}}}}</ref> On the 12 July 1961, the state adopted a constitution turning itself into the Federated State of South Kasai (''\u00c9tat f\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9 du Sud-Kasa\u00ef''), declaring the state itself both \"sovereign and democratic\" but also part of a hypothetical \"Federal Republic of the Congo\".{{sfn|Dufresne|2011|p=26}} The constitution also provided for a bicameral legislature, with a lower chamber composed of all national deputies, senators, and provincial assemblymen elected in constituencies within South Kasai's territory, and an upper chamber filled by traditional chiefs.{{sfn|Young|1965|p=395}} The state had its own flag, published its own [[official journal]], the ''Moniteur de l'\u00c9tat Autonome du Sud-Kasa\u00ef'',{{sfn|Dufresne|2011|pp=25\u20136}} and even produced its own [[postage stamp]]s{{efn|South Kasai issued a total of 28 unique postage stamps and one [[souvenir sheet]], all in 1961.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://www.linns.com/news/world-stamps-postal-history/2017/september/south-kasai-stamps-spreadsheet-images-inside-linns.html#| title = The stamps of short-lived South Kasai, spreadsheet stamp images: Inside Linn's| last = Snee| first = Charles| date = 15 September 2017| website = [[Linn's Stamp News]]| publisher = Amos Media Company| access-date = 28 December 2017}}</ref>}} and [[vehicle registration plate]]s.{{sfn|Packham|1996|p=71}}<ref name= halberstam/> Unlike Katanga, South Kasai maintained no diplomatic missions abroad.<ref name= garrison/>\n\nThe South Kasaian army or [[gendarmerie]] grew from just 250 members at its inception to nearly 3,000 by 1961.{{sfn|Willame|1972|pp=66\u20137}} It was led by 22-year-old \"General\" Floribert Dinanga with the assistance of nine European officers.{{sfn|Young|1965|p=454}} In 1961, the military led a campaign to expand the size of the state's territory at the expense of neighbouring ethnic groups.{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=67}} Despite receiving some support from Belgium, the gendarmerie was poorly equipped and constantly low on supplies and ammunition.{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=67}}\n\nAs government authority in South Kasai was consolidated, the regime became increasingly militaristic and authoritarian.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=106}} Non-Luba groups were increasingly marginalised.{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=67}} Political opponents were killed or driven into exile, including Ngalula, who had a falling out with Kalonji in July 1961.{{sfn|Packham|1996|p=90}} Non-Luba groups in the region, especially the Kanyok, fought a constant but low-level insurgency against the South Kasaian government.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=106}}\n\n===International support===\n[[File:Diamond-27425.jpg|thumb|upright|An uncut [[diamond|yellow diamond]] from South Kasai; diamond exporting was a major asset to the state.]]\nKalonji went to great lengths to secure international recognition and support for the state of South Kasai. The former colonial power, Belgium, distrusted the Congolese central government and supported both the governments of South Kasai and Katanga. Like Katanga, South Kasai had important mineral deposits, including [[diamond]] fields, and Belgian companies had large sums of money tied up in mines in the area. A Belgian company, {{lang|fr|[[Formini\u00e8re]]}}, was the state's principal supporter and received concessions from South Kasai in exchange for financial support.{{sfn|Nugent|2004|p=86}} The comparatively large income from these companies{{efn|An administrator of the [[Societ\u00e9 Mini\u00e8re de Bakwanga]] estimated that his company paid approximately $12,000,000 in taxes annually to the South Kasaian government. Other Belgians estimated that the regime, in taking half of the diamond mines' profits, extracted BEF 350,000,000 ($7,000,000) per year and an additional BEF 235,000,000 ($4,700,000) in excise taxes.<ref name= halberstam/>}} meant that South Kasai was able to support significant public services and cope with large numbers of [[internally displaced persons|internally-displaced]] Luba refugees.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=106}} In the context of the [[Cold War]], Kalonji was supported by Western powers and moderates in the Congolese government who viewed him as both a moderate [[Western world|pro-Westerner]] and [[anticommunism|anticommunist]].{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=106}} Although both Katanga and South Kasai were supported by [[Union of South Africa|South Africa]], [[French Fifth Republic|France]] and the [[Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland|Central African Federation]], neither state ever received any form of official [[diplomatic recognition]].{{sfn|Nugent|2004|pp=97}}{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=101}}\n\nAfter the coup d'\u00e9tat which removed Lumumba from power, Kalonji tried to cultivate good relations with the Congolese government.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=106}} [[Mobutu Sese Seko|Joseph-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Mobutu]], in particular, was able to use South Kasai for the execution of his political opponents and dissident Lumumbists including [[Jean-Pierre Finant]].{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=106}} Such activity led the secessionist state to be nicknamed \"the national butcher's yard\".{{sfn|Kanza|1994|p=325}}\n\n===Kalonji as ''Mulopwe''===\nBecause of the importance of the Luba ethnicity to South Kasai, Kalonji used his support from the traditional Luba tribal authorities to have himself declared ''Mulopwe''.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=105}} The title, ''Mulopwe'' (usually translated as \"King\" or \"Emperor\"), was extremely symbolic because it was the title employed by the rulers of the pre-colonial Luba Empire and had been disused since the 1880s. By taking it, along with the extra name ''Ditunga'' (\"homeland\"), Kalonji was able to closely tie himself and the South Kasaian state to the Luba Empire to increase its legitimacy in the eyes of the Baluba.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=105}} In order to avoid accusations of impropriety, the title was bestowed on Kalonji's father on 12 April 1961, who then immediately abdicated in favour of his son. With the accession of Kalonji to the title of ''Mulopwe'' on 16 July, the state's title changed to the Federated Kingdom of South Kasai (''Royaume f\u00e9d\u00e9r\u00e9 du Sud-Kasa\u00ef'').{{sfn|Gondola|2002|p=187}}\n\nKalonji's accession to the position of ''Mulopwe'' was heavily criticised even by many Luba in South Kasai.{{sfn|Packham|1996|p=66}}{{efn|Some Kalonji detractors noted that the Luba Empire was historically centered in Katanga, not Kasai, and that the Kasai Baluba had never been led by a ''Mulopwe''.{{sfn|Young|1965|p=396}}}} Kalonji remained popular among some groups, but lost the support of the South Kasaian ''\u00e9volu\u00e9s'' who saw his elevation as flagrant opportunism. Soon after his elevation, Kalonji was publicly condemned and disavowed by 10 of South Kasai's 13 representatives in the L\u00e9opoldville Parliament, beginning the disintegration of the secessionist state.{{sfn|Packham|1996|p=66}}\n\n==Collapse and reintegration==\n\n===Campaign of August\u2013September 1960===\nWhen South Kasai seceded, government troops from the ''[[Arm\u00e9e Nationale Congolaise]]'' (ANC) were already fighting Katangese troops in the Kasai region.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=105}} South Kasai held important railway junctions needed by the Congolese army for its campaign in Katanga, and therefore soon became an important objective.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|pp=105\u20136}} South Kasai also had important mineral wealth which the central government was anxious to return to the Congo.{{sfn|Haskin|2005|p=5}} The central government also misunderstood the South Kasaian position, believing that, like Katanga, the region had declared full independence from the Congo and rejected Congolese sovereignty.{{sfn|Le Potentiel|2008}}\n\n{{Quote box|width=246px|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|align=left|quote=\"[The actions of the ANC in South Kasai] involve a most flagrant violation of elementary [[human rights]] and have the characteristics of the crime of [[genocide]] since they appear to be directed towards the extermination of a specific ethnic group, the Balubas{{sic}}.\"|source=[[Dag Hammarskj\u00f6ld]], UN Secretary-General, September 1960{{sfn|Bring|2011|p=160}}}}\nInitially, Lumumba hoped that the [[United Nations]] (UN), which sent [[United Nations Operation in the Congo|a multi-national peacekeeping force]] to the Congo in July 1960, would help the central government suppress both Katangese and South Kasaian secessions. The UN was reluctant to do so, however, considering the secessions to be internal political matters and its own mission to be maintaining basic law and order.{{sfn|Haskin|2005|pp=5, 23}} Rejected by both the UN and [[United States]], Lumumba sought military support from the communist [[Soviet Union]].{{sfn|Haskin|2005|p=5}} Within days of the secession and with Soviet logistical support, 2,000 ANC troops launched a major offensive against South Kasai.{{sfn|Zeilig|2008|p=114}} The attack was extremely successful. On 27 August, ANC soldiers arrived in Bakwanga.{{sfn|Packham|1996|p=38}}\n\nDuring the course of the offensive, the ANC became involved in ethnic violence between the Baluba and Bena Lulua.{{sfn|Zeilig|2008|p=114}} When government troops arrived in Bakwanga, they released Lulua tribesmen from prison and began requisitioning civilian vehicles. When David Odia, the South Kasai Minister of Public Works, protested, soldiers beat him and fatally injured him. Many Baluba first fled in terror, but then began resisting with home-made shotguns.{{sfn|Hoskyns|1965|p=194}} As a result, the ANC perpetrated a number of large massacres of Luba civilians.{{sfn|Zeilig|2008|p=114}} In September, [[Dag Hammarskj\u00f6ld]], the [[UN Secretary-General]] who had recently deployed a large peacekeeping force to the Congo, referred to the massacres as \"a case of incipient genocide\".{{sfn|Bring|2011|p=160}} The Baluba were also attacked by the Katangese from the south.{{sfn|Haskin|2005|p=26}} In the ensuring massacres, in which ANC or Katangese troops often participated, around 3,000 Baluba were killed.{{sfn|Haskin|2005|p=26}} The violence of the advance caused an exodus of many thousands of Luba civilians who fled their homes to escape the fighting; more than 35,000 went to refugee camps in [[Lubumbashi|\u00c9lisabethville]] (the capital of Katanga) alone.{{sfn|Haskin|2005|p=33}} As many as 100,000 sought refuge in Bakwanga.{{sfn|UNCHS|1991|p=129}} Diseases, notably [[kwashiorkor]] but also [[malaria]], [[smallpox]] and [[anemia]], were widespread and reached \"epidemic proportions\" among Luba refugees between October and December 1960.{{sfn|Lowenstein|1962|p=751}} The [[World Health Organization]] sent one million small pox vaccines to South Kasai to alleviate the problem. The epidemic had been preceded by widespread famine which by December was killing an estimated 200 people daily. The UN appealed to its member states for relief, and by late January government and private aid had reduced mortality by 75 percent. Further assistance in the form of an emergency food airlift, additional medical personnel, and seeds from the [[Food and Agriculture Organization]] ensured that the famine was almost entirely resolved by March 1961.{{sfn|Simmonds|2012|pp=243\u2013244}} \n\nAllegations of genocide{{efn|Though there has been little study of the ANC atrocities in South Kasai, no information has ever been presented to corroborate the notion that Lumumba or other officials intended to eliminate certain populations and the use of the term \"genocide\" was primarily a rhetorical device meant to damage his reputation.{{sfn|Stapleton|2017|p=92}}}} and brutality by the ANC were used to provide legitimacy to Kasa-Vubu's dismissal of Lumumba, with the support of Mobutu, in September 1960.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=102}} In the aftermath of the campaign, the South Kasaian state was able to provide substantial aid to its refugees, many of whom were resettled in homes and jobs.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=106}} Nevertheless, the invasion caused considerable disruption to the local economy; by December the number of diamonds cut by Formini\u00e8re and the number of people it employed both had fallen by thousands.{{sfn|Hoskyns|1965|p=286}}\n\n===Coexistence and attempted reconciliation===\n[[File:Kalonji and Kasa-Vubu.jpg|thumb|Kalonji with Congolese President [[Joseph Kasa-Vubu]] in 1961]]\nDespite the occupation of South Kasai, the South Kasaian state was not dismantled and co-existed with the rest of the Congo. Congolese delegates, as well as ANC and UN troops were generally able to move around the territory without conflict with the South Kasaian authorities while their sporadic campaign against Katangese forces continued.{{sfn|Le Potentiel|2008}} A UN-sponsored ceasefire in September 1960 gave pause to the Luba-Lulua conflict, but by November Kalonji's forces had broken the truce.<ref>{{cite news| last = Hofmann| first = Paul| title = 'Civil War' in South Kasai Reported by U.N. in Congo| newspaper = The New York Times| pages = 1, 8| date = 3 November 1960| id = {{ProQuest|115109726}}}}</ref> Throughout much of the period, the South Kasaian gendarmerie fought with Kanyok and Lulua militias across the region while local ethnic violence persisted.{{sfn|Packham|1996|p=40}}\n\nIn mid-1961, conferences were held at [[Mbandaka|Coquilhatville]] (modern-day Mbandaka) and later in [[Antananarivo]], [[Malagasy Republic|Madagascar]] to attempt to broker a peaceful reconciliation between the secessionist factions and the central government in the face of a [[Free Republic of the Congo|rebel government]] in the Eastern Congo led by [[Antoine Gizenga]].{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=37}} It was believed that, with Lumumba dead, it might be possible to create a federal constitution that could reconcile the three parties.{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=37}} The agreements instead led to more uncertainty.{{sfn|Willame|1972|pp=37\u20138}} The ousting of Ngalula\u2014the chief organiser of the South Kasai state\u2014in July hastened internal collapse.{{sfn|Young|1965|p=396}} He established his own political party, the Democratic Union, to oppose the Kalonjists.{{sfn|Packham|1996|p=111}} Later that month Parliament reconvened with Kalonji and the other South Kasain deputies in attendance. A new government was formed on 2 August with Ngalula as Minister of Education, and Kalonji went back to South Kasai.{{sfn|Hoskyns|1965|pp=374, 377}} In late October 1961 Kalonji and several Lulua leaders made a symbolic union in an attempt to end the Luba-Lulua tribal conflict.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2014|p=217}}\n\n===Kalonji's arrest===\n[[File:Kongo 1961 map en.png|thumb|left|Map showing the situation in the Congo in 1961 with the territory split between four opposing factions]]\nOn 2 December 1961, Kalonji was accused by another deputy, the communist [[Christophe Gbenye]], of having ordered [[corporal punishment]] against a political prisoner in South Kasai.{{sfn|Packham|1996|p=88}} Parliament voted to remove Kalonji's [[political immunity]] and he was taken into custody by the ANC in L\u00e9opoldville.{{sfn|Packham|1996|pp=88\u20139}} A delegation of around 400 Luba tribal elders sent to L\u00e9opoldville to protest were also briefly arrested.{{sfn|Packham|1996|p=89}} Mobutu and [[Victor Lundula]] visited Bakwanga soon afterwards.{{sfn|Packham|1996|p=40}} [[Ferdinand Kazadi]] assumed power as acting head of state of South Kasai.<ref name= halberstam/>\n\nOn 9 March 1962, the recently re-convened L\u00e9opoldville Parliament, under Prime Minister Cyrille Adoula, agreed to modify the Constitution and gave South Kasai official provincial status.{{sfn|Le Potentiel|2008}} In April 1962, UN troops were ordered to occupy South Kasai as part of Secretary-General  [[U Thant]]'s new aggressive stance against secession following Hammarskj\u00f6ld's death. In L\u00e9opoldville, Kalonji was sentenced to five years' imprisonment.{{sfn|Packham|1996|p=40}} On 7 September, however, Kalonji escaped from prison and returned to South Kasai where he hoped to regain an official position in local elections and, at the head of a government, regain his immunity.{{sfn|Packham|1996|pp=40; 155}}\n\n===Coup d'\u00e9tat of 1962===\nAs dissatisfaction with the secession grew, Ngalula and other South Kasaian \u00e9migr\u00e9s in L\u00e9opoldville plotted to overthrow the regime in Bakwanga. In September 1962, the L\u00e9opoldville government appointed Albert Kankolongo as Special Commissioner (''commissaire extraordinaire'') for South Kasai, giving him full military and civil power, to dismantle the local state. Ngalula approached Kankolongo to lead a mutiny and coup d'\u00e9tat against Kalonji.{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=67}}\n\nOn the night of 29/30 September 1962, military commanders in South Kasai, led by Kankolongo, launched a coup d'\u00e9tat in Bakwanga against the Kalonjist regime.{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=106}}{{sfn|Le Potentiel|2008}} The coup d'\u00e9tat was followed by calls for South Kasai to be fully re-integrated into the Congo.{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=68}} Kalonji rode around the capital for three days and attempted to rally support for his cause. Facing intense opposition, he retreated to his residence. His bodyguards delayed an attack from the mutineers while he escaped, taking a lorry to Katanga.{{sfn|Othen|2015|loc=Chapter 24: The Flying Horror}} On 5 October 1962, central government troops again arrived in Bakwanga to support the mutineers and help suppress the last Kalonjist loyalists, marking the end of the secession.{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=68}} Kalonji took up residence in [[Kamina]] and attempted to meet Tshombe, but was rebuffed by Katangese Minister of Interior [[Godefroid Munongo]]. He then fled to [[Paris]]{{sfn|Othen|2015|loc=Chapter 24: The Flying Horror}} before settling in [[Barcelona]] in [[Francisco Franco]]'s [[Francoist Spain|Spain]].{{sfn|Congo Ind\u00e9pendant|2010}} General Dinanga also fled.{{sfn|Young|1965|p=455}}\n\n==Aftermath==\n\n===In Kasai===\n[[File:Reconciliation stamp, Congo L\u00e9opoldville 1963.jpg|thumb|1963 stamp celebrating the \"reconciliation\" of South Kasai and Katanga with the Congolese central government]]\nIn October 1962, South Kasai returned to the Republic of the Congo. The State of Katanga continued to hold out against the central government until it too collapsed in January 1963 after UN forces began to take a more aggressive stance under Thant.{{sfn|Boulden|2001|p=40}} As a compromise, South Kasai was one of the 21 provinces formally established by the [[Luluabourg Constitution|federalist constitution]] of 1964. As the Mobutu regime launched a centralist restructuring of the Congolese state from 1965, South Kasai was one of the few provinces which were retained. The province was later restructured to include new territory in [[Kabinda District|Kabinda]] and [[Sankuru District]]s and renamed [[Kasai-Oriental|Eastern Kasai]] (''Kasa\u00ef-Oriental'').{{sfn|Nzongola-Ntalaja|2007|p=106}}\n\nThe majority of the South Kasaian soldiers were integrated into the ANC after the dissolution of the state but nearly 2,000 loyalists went into hiding to await Kalonji's possible restoration. The rebels were led by General Mwanzambala and fought a guerrilla war against the new provincial government until 1963 when they also accepted integration into the ANC.{{sfn|Willame|1972|p=68}} Soon after the end of the secession, the city of Bakwanga was renamed Mbuji-Mayi after the local river in an attempt to signify a Luba intra-ethnicity reconciliation. Regardless, violence among Luba factions lasted through 1964, and a political solution was not reached until 1965 with the election of J. Munkamba as Provincial President of South Kasai.{{sfn|Pandey|Geschiere|2003|p=203}}\n\n===End of the Congo Crisis===\nIn 1965, Mobutu launched a second coup d'\u00e9tat against the central government and took personal [[emergency powers]]. Once established as the sole source of political power, Mobutu gradually consolidated his control in the Congo. The number of provinces was reduced, and their autonomy curtailed, resulting in a highly centralised state. Mobutu increasingly placed his supporters in the remaining positions of importance.{{sfn|Nugent|2004|p=233}} In 1967, to illustrate his legitimacy, he created a party, the [[Popular Movement of the Revolution]] (MPR), which until 1990 was the nation's only legal political party under Mobutu's revised constitution.{{sfn|Nugent|2004|p=233}} In 1971, the state was renamed [[Zaire]] and efforts were made [[Authenticit\u00e9 (Zaire)|to remove all colonial influences]]. He also nationalised the remaining foreign-owned economic assets in the country.{{sfn|Nugent|2004|pp=234\u20135}} Over time Zaire was increasingly characterised by widespread [[croneyism]], corruption and economic mismanagement.{{sfn|Nugent|2004|pp=236\u20139}} Dissatisfaction with the regime in ''Kasa\u00ef-Oriental'' was particularly strong.{{sfn|French|2007|pp=117, 119}}\n\nThe issues of federalism, ethnicity in politics and state centralisation were not resolved by the crisis and partly contributed to a decline in support for the concept of the state among Congolese people.{{sfn|Turner|2007|p=185}} Mobutu was strongly in favour of centralisation and one of his first acts, in 1965, were to reunify provinces and abolish much of their independent legislative capacity.{{sfn|Turner|2007|p=117}} Subsequent loss of faith in central government is one of the reasons that the Congo has been labeled as a [[failed state]], and has contributed violence by factions advocating ethnic and localised federalism.{{sfn|Turner|2007|p=185}}\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Democratic Republic of the Congo}}\n* [[Decolonisation of Africa]]\n* [[Conflict diamonds]]\n* [[Biafra]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{Notelist}}\n\n===References===\n{{Reflist|colwidth=20em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|ref={{harvid|Boulden|2001}}|last1=Boulden|first1=Jane|title=Peace Enforcement: The United Nations Experience in Congo, Somalia, and Bosnia|date=2001|publisher=Praeger|location=Westport, Conn.|isbn=0-275-96906-1|edition=1st}}\n* {{cite book|ref={{harvid|Bring|2011}}|last=Bring|first=Ove|title=Hammarskj\u00f6ld's approach to the United Nations and international law|series=Documentos|year=2011|publisher=Instituto de estudios internacionales|location=Chile}}\n* {{cite web|ref={{harvid|EISA|2002}}|title=DRC: Background to the 1965 election|url=http://www.content.eisa.org.za/old-page/drc-background-1965-election|publisher=Electoral Institute for Sustainable Democracy in Africa (EISA)|accessdate=8 July 2014|url-status=dead|archive